answers.body_markdown:
The second version is better because it separates the concerns of (a) calculating the area from (b) what to do with the results.

You don&#39;t need to declare `double area = 0` before you assign a value to it. You can simply write:

    double area = 3.14 * r * r;

But, in fact, you don&#39;t need to declare a variable at all in that method. You can return the value.

    public static double area(double r){
        return 3.14 * r * r;
    }

You can also use the Math constant for PI:

    public static double areaOfCircle(double r){
        return Math.PI * r * r;
    }

