I&#39;ll post something that might help because it&#39;s not 100% clear what is wrong with what you&#39;ve received so far. The following will size the caption to a fraction of the entire image width (currently a quarter). Obviously you need to remove the &#39;magic numbers&#39; and tweak according to your requirements and remove any hard-coding remaining. I&#39;ll say right off that it&#39;s not really the &#39;proper&#39; way of doing it, since the correct transformation should be applied without looping, probably via something like an ```AffineTransform```  with the correct geometry from the start to derive the font.

    import javax.imageio.ImageIO;
    import java.awt.*;
    import java.awt.geom.*;
    import java.awt.image.BufferedImage;
    import java.io.File;
    import java.net.URL;
    
    public class InternetSample {
    
        public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
            final BufferedImage image = ImageIO.read(new File(args[0]));
            Font font = new Font(&quot;Arial&quot;, Font.BOLD, 1);
            Graphics g = image.getGraphics();
            String caption = &quot;Welcome To Taj Mahal!&quot;;
            getFontSizedForCaption(image, caption, font, g);
            g.drawString(caption, 100, 100);
            g.dispose();
            ImageIO.write(image, &quot;png&quot;, new File(&quot;Taj_Mahal.png&quot;));
        }
    
        static Font getFontSizedForCaption(BufferedImage img, String caption, Font startFont, Graphics g) {
            Font derivedFont = startFont;
            int imgWidth = img.getWidth();
            float fontSize = 1.0f;
            double captionWidth = 0.0;
            // Fraction of the image width that the caption width takes up
            while (captionWidth &lt; (imgWidth / 4)) {
                derivedFont = derivedFont.deriveFont(fontSize);
                g.setFont(derivedFont);
                FontMetrics fm = g.getFontMetrics();
                Rectangle2D captionRect = fm.getStringBounds(caption, g);
                captionWidth = captionRect.getWidth();
                //System.out.printf(&quot;Width now %.2f%n&quot;, captionRect.getWidth());
                fontSize += 5.0f;
            }
            return derivedFont;
        }
    }

Your font is rendered based on the image quality, a good way in my opinion is to multiply the font with a factor to resize it based on the image size, the following function might help you 

    /**
     * compute a factor for different image qualities
     *
     * @param image the image to compute the factor
     * @param coefficient to scale the factor
     * @return
     */
    private static double getImageFactor(BufferedImage image, int coefficient) {
        Dimension screenSize = Toolkit.getDefaultToolkit().getScreenSize();
        double screenSizeWidth = screenSize.getWidth();
        double screenSizeHeight = screenSize.getHeight();
        double screenHypotenuse = Math.sqrt(screenSizeWidth * screenSizeWidth + screenSizeHeight * screenSizeHeight);

        Rectangle bounds = image.getData().getBounds();
        double imageWidth = bounds.getWidth();
        double imageHeight = bounds.getHeight();
        double imageHypotenuse = Math.sqrt(imageWidth * imageWidth + imageHeight * imageHeight);

        return imageHypotenuse * coefficient / (screenHypotenuse + screenHypotenuse);
    }

and in order to use it you can call it with a coefficient which might be decided by you

    Font font = new Font(&quot;Arial&quot;, Font.BOLD, (int) (32 * getImageFactor(image, 2)));


note that there might be a more delicate way to compute the factor but in this case it might suffice.

